[1] China (Beijing) outbreak: update
Date: Wed 17 Jun 2020 08:42 am IST
Source: NDTV, Agence France-Presse (AFP) report [edited]
https://www.ndtv.com/world-news/coronavirus-more-than-1-200-flights-cancelled-in-beijing-over-covid-19-fears-2247436


Beijing's airports cancelled more than 1200 flights and schools in the Chinese capital were closed again on Wednesday [17 Jun 2020] as authorities rushed to contain a new coronavirus outbreak linked to a wholesale food market. The city reported 31 new cases on Wednesday [17 Jun 2020], while officials urged residents not to leave Beijing, with fears growing about a 2nd wave of infections in China, which had largely brought its outbreak under control.

Tens of thousands of people linked to the new Beijing virus cluster -- believed to have started in the sprawling Xinfadi wholesale food market -- are being tested, with almost 30 residential compounds in the city now under lockdown.

At least 1255 scheduled flights were cancelled on Wednesday morning [17 Jun 2020], state-run People's Daily reported, nearly 70 per cent of all trips to and from Beijing's main airports. The outbreak had already forced authorities to announce a travel ban for residents of "medium- or high-risk" areas of the city while requiring other residents to take nucleic acid tests in order to leave Beijing.

Meanwhile, several provinces were quarantining travellers from Beijing, where all schools -- which had mostly reopened -- have been ordered to close again and return to online classes. "The epidemic situation in the capital is extremely severe," Beijing city spokesman Xu Hejian warned Tuesday [16 Jun 2020].

Mass testing under way
----------------------
Officials have closed 11 markets and disinfected thousands of food and beverage businesses in Beijing since the outbreak was detected. The city has now reported 137 infections over the last 6 days, with 6 new asymptomatic cases and 3 suspected cases on Wednesday [17 Jun 2020], according to the municipal health commission. An additional 2 domestic cases, one in neighbouring Hebei province and another in Zhejiang, were reported by national authorities on Wednesday [17 Jun 2020], while there were 11 imported cases.

Authorities have so far banned group sports, ordered people to wear masks in crowded enclosed spaces, and suspended inter-provincial group tours in response to the outbreak.

Officials said that since [30 May 2020], more than 200 000 people had visited Xinfadi market, which supplies more than 70 per cent of Beijing's fruit and vegetables. More than 8000 workers there were tested and quarantined.

Until the new outbreak, most of China's recent cases were nationals returning from abroad as COVID-19 spread globally, and the government had all but declared victory against the disease. China's Center for Disease Control and Prevention said on Monday [15 Jun 2020] that the virus type found in the Beijing outbreak was a "major epidemic strain" in Europe.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The media report mentions the additional measures of shutting down air traffic and discouraging inter provincial travel. Effectively, a lockdown is being put into place, focused on the areas around the market. One suspects this lockdown may be expanded geographically as more contacts are identified.

We still await further information on additional genomic studies in the attempt to identify the location of origin of the virus. Other media reports have mentioned that salmon importations are being halted (see Asia One for more details on the salmon https://www.asiaone.com/china/coronavirus-china-halts-salmon-imports-over-possible-link-beijing-outbreak-consumers-leap). In this article, Marion Koopmans at the Erasmus University Medical Centre in Rotterdam raised concern of a "European strain" in the absence of data addressing the diversity of viruses in China.

A map of China showing provinces can be found at https://sacu.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/provmap.png and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7477998,353. - Mod.MPP]

